istry_(Wade)/03%3A_Structure_and_Stereochemistry_of_Alkanes/4.11%3A_Joined_Rings";s:6:"domain";s:19:"chem.libretexts.org";}}s:9:"sentences";a:61:{i:0;s:235:"Therefore in the chair-chair form of trans decalin the arrangement of the substituent was fixed whereas they are relatively flexible in the chair form of the cis decalin was and the conversion of two rings at once occurs fairly easily.";i:1;s:90:"Hence the substituent can be interconverted between the equatorial and axial conformation.";i:2;s:62:"In decalins both cyclohexane rings are in chair conformations.";i:3;s:182:"The trans structure highlighted blue hydrogens trans is a flat rather rigid structure however the cis structures are puckered due to the ring junction highlighted blue hydrogens cis.";i:4;s:83:"Draw the following decalin as a chair conformation in the most stable conformation.";i:5;s:55:"Ask unlimited questions and get expert help right away.";i:6;s:124:"Now we shall consider trans-decalin itselfThe most stable conformation of this isomer has both rings in chair conformations.";i:7;s:177:"While there is some mobility for each ring to undergo subtle conformational change it is not possible for either ring to undergo conformational inversion to the alternate chair.";i:8;s:62:"Draw The Chair Conformations Of Cis-decalin And Trans-decalin.";i:9;s:29:"This problem has been solved.";i:10;s:92:"Can someone help me with drawing the chair conformations of cis-descalin and trans-descalin.";i:11;s:28:"Show transcribed image text.";i:12;s:59:"Expert Answer 100 1 rating Previous question Next question.";i:13;s:32:"Favored conformation is a chair.";i:14;s:42:"Axial and Equatorial Bonds in Cyclohexane.";i:15;s:124:"Cis- and trans-decalin are stereoisomers they do not interconvert into each other H H H H H H H H trans-decalin cis-decalin.";i:16;s:54:"83109 12 CH 3 H HO H H3C H3C HO H H H3C H Cholesterol.";i:17;s:121:"The trans-decalin is represented with different drawings but they represent the same molecule viewed at different angles.";i:18;s:157:"Notice that trans-decalin cannot undergo a ring-flip while cis-decalin can undergo a ring flip and the resulting structures are conformational stereoisomers.";i:19;s:106:"The cis and trans-decalin on the other hand are configurational isomers and cannot interconvert through a.";i:20;s:21:"Complete a 2nd chair.";i:21;s:68:"Substituent X is now axial to ring A and equatorial to ring B while.";i:22;s:62:"Substituent Y is now axial to ring B and equatorial to ring A.";i:23;s:50:"Now draw the chair conformation for trans decalin.";i:24;s:98:"Step 1 is to also start out with just 1 chair normally and write in carbon 1 and carbon 2 like so.";i:25;s:144:"Step 2 is to also draw in the Hydrogens because it is a lot easier and then allocate which Carbons are bridgehead Carbons which are carbons 1 2.";i:26;s:66:"Both cis- and trans-decalin have two equivalent planar structures.";i:27;s:75:"Each cyclohexane ring in cis-decalin can undergo the chair interconversion.";i:28;s:101:"You should verify with models that when one ring changes its conformation the other must change also.";i:29;s:88:"However in trans-decalin the six-membered rings can assume twist-boat conformations but.";i:30;s:183:"A trans-decalin template is provided - put in the two methyl groups trans to each other at the ring-junction carbons and then draw in the bromine atom with the proper stereochemistry.";i:31;s:71:"Proceed with the analysis as you would with the monocyclic cyclohexane.";i:32;s:126:"For cis-decalin using cis-decalin 1 for the sake of discussion clearly has 13-diaxial interactions gauche butane interactions.";i:33;s:67:"How many gauche interactions are present in the chair conformation.";i:34;s:51:"Recall that a chair-chair conformational inversion.";i:35;s:150:"Hexanes the preferred conformation is provided dipolar interactions are not dominant that with the maximum possible number of substituents equatorial.";i:36;s:142:"When two cyclohexane rings are fused together as in the configurational isomers trans- VII and cis- VIII decalin a unique two-chair conforma-.";i:37;s:391:"Lets get some practice drawing it chair confirmations one way to do it is to start by drawing two parallel lines that are offset from each others let me go ahead and show you what I mean so heres heres one line and then here is another line theyre parallel to each other but theyre offset a little bit next were going to draw two horizontal dotted lines so the top horizontal dotted line is.";i:38;s:126:"The chair conformation is considerably more stable and comprises more than 999 of the equilibrium mixture at room temperature.";i:39;s:111:"Chair left and boat right conformations of the six carbons of a cyclohexane ring with normal C-C-C bond angles.";i:40;s:178:"For trans-decalin with both rings in chair conformation there is even no need to change your drawing for pseudo-3D red plane refers to the plane of drawing not symmetry scheme A.";i:41;s:99:"Also note that in crystallography there are also plus and minus signs used for the same purpose eg.";i:42;s:45:"Denoting an object including atoms that lies.";i:43;s:126:"A chair conformation with an axial substituent is less stable compared to a chair conformation with an equatorial substituent.";i:44;s:54:"Note that only cis-decalin is capable of a chair flip.";i:45;s:142:"In trans-decalin a chair flip would result in two axial carboncarbon bonds with the remaining bonds too far apart to close a cyclohexane ring.";i:46;s:111:"The most stable conformation of both isomers of decalin is one in which both rings take on chair conformations.";i:47;s:90:"Drawing the cis isomer is a bit tricky because one of the chairs has to be drawn sideways.";i:48;s:100:"While the cis isomer can take on two conformations via simultaneous chair flips the trans isomer is.";i:49;s:64:"Number the ring and draw any chair conformation of the compound.";i:50;s:73:"Draw the second chair conformation ring-flip-check this post if not